    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{5}{6t}+\frac{2}{3t}}={5}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{\frac{3}{10}\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{18t}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{5}{6t}+\frac{2}{3t}} \amp = {5} \\
  {\frac{5}{6t}\cdot 18t+\frac{2}{3t}\cdot 18t} \amp = {5\cdot 18t} \\
  15+12 \amp = {90t} \\
  27 \amp = {90t} \\
  \frac{27}{90} \amp = \frac{{90t}}{90} \\
  {\left\{\frac{3}{10}\right\}} \amp = t \\
  t \amp  = {\left\{\frac{3}{10}\right\}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>t \ne 0</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>t = {\left\{\frac{3}{10}\right\}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
